 {"id":"mu-k4i3","title":"Audit goal-protocol skill vs current mu-slat orchestration, then dogfood orchestration on first scaffolding-epic item","description":"Two-part follow-up, sequenced AFTER mu-d04a (streaming rework) and after the #3 scaffolding epic is planned. Raised by operator 2026-05-28.\n\n## Part 1 — bring goal-protocol skill into compliance with current orchestration\nThe mu-slat orchestration evolved substantially (esp. 2026-05-28): host-side reap on result-post, Rust-owned pty + vt100 cadence spawn (replacing script(1)), mu-spawn linux-fs mounts (linprocfs/linsysfs/tmpfs-shm/fdescfs-linrdlnk for the CPU fix), and the reply_to→calling-session fix (mu-d04a's sibling, commit 03015a51). The goal-protocol skill (~/.claude-personal/skills/goal-protocol) predates most of this. Audit it against the current spawn_worker / pot lifecycle / mailbox-result / reap reality and reconcile any drift.\n\n## Part 2 — dogfood\nOnce the #3 scaffolding epic exists, dispatch its FIRST item through the orchestration (spawn_worker / a goal session) rather than doing it by hand — a real-world test of the loop on non-toy work. Watch: does the worker complete + post a usable result, does reap fire, does the result wake the operator session (the mu-d04a behavior).\n\n## Provenance\nOperator aside during the mu-d04a planning session, 2026-05-28.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-05-28T20:28:09.867651801Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-28T20:28:09.867651801Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["dogfood","goal-protocol","mu-slat","orchestration"]}
 {"id":"mu-k56u","title":"mid-session provider/model switching: set_route RPC + two-step picker","description":"Enable switching provider and model mid-session without restarting.\n\n## Daemon side\n- New RPC: session.set_route { provider, model } — atomic, validated\n- Between turns: tear down current provider, rebuild with new one\n- Log a model-change event to the event log\n- Decompose create_session into new_session + set_route (create_session becomes sugar)\n- Rehydration analogy: mid-session switch = rehydrate against different backend\n\n## Daemon discovery\n- daemon.list_providers RPC: returns available providers with configured status + model lists\n- Hide unconfigured/credentialless providers from the picker\n\n## mu-solo UX\n- Two-step picker: select provider first, then model filtered to that provider\n- One atomic set_route sent only after both selected (no transient invalid state)\n- Favorites/short-list from solo.toml config, full list behind 'more' separator\n- /provider and /model commands become live (currently display-only stubs)\n\n## Cache behavior\n- Event log and rope unchanged on switch\n- Re-project through new provider's tokenizer on next ask\n- Cache invalidation is the provider's problem (different model = different prefix hash = cache miss, correct behavior)\n\nPriority: daily-driver QoL, near 6/15 path.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-05-27T16:53:31.799052803Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-27T20:48:16.680992053Z","closed_at":"2026-05-27T20:48:16.680900611Z","close_reason":"Landed in two commits (c840a0e8 + 445af3d5). RouteCatalog with env-probing + hash validation, ProviderSwitched event (Arc<str> beachhead), SwitchProvider AgentInput handled at turn boundaries, session.set_route + daemon.list_routes RPCs, mu-solo /model and /provider commands wired live. Remaining from bead scope: two-step inline picker (using modal picker for now), favorites/short-list from solo.toml, catalog as MCP resource (mu://routes/available), decomposing create_session.","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","daily-driver","model","mu-solo","provider","rpc","session"]}
 {"id":"mu-k591","title":"mu-agent-loop: cap consecutive tool-not-found responses (force end_turn after N=3 default)","description":"## Problem\n\nThe agent loop in `crates/mu-core/src/agent/loop_/mod.rs` has no termination guard for repeated `\"tool not found\"` responses. When a model emits `stop_reason: \"tool_use\"` for a tool that mu hasn't registered, the dispatcher returns a tool_result with error message `\"tool not found: <name>\"`, and the loop continues. Some models will then try a different (also-nonexistent) tool name, and the loop spins until the model gives up on its own.\n\nThis is the same loop observed in mu-q3v6's validation reproducer: 6 consecutive tool_use turns chasing hallucinated tools before Gemini-3.5-flash finally emitted end_turn. Each round burned ~30k prompt tokens.\n\n## Why a defensive guard even after the sibling bead lands\n\nSibling bead [the no-tools-clause one] addresses the root cause for the `tool_count == 0` case. But:\n\n1. Some providers/models may emit tool_use even when explicitly told not to (prompt non-adherence is not zero).\n2. The same pattern can arise with `tool_count > 0` if the model hallucinates a tool name that isn't in the registered set. Today: a session with one registered tool (e.g. `bash`) and a model that emits `execute_bash` will get \"tool not found\" → loop continues.\n3. Even with a clean system prompt, providers under load may produce degraded outputs that retry-loop.\n\nA defensive cap is a belt-and-suspenders safety net. It says: \"regardless of what the system prompt said, if the model has emitted N consecutive tool_calls that don't resolve, force end_turn.\"\n\n## Proposal\n\nIn the agent loop, track consecutive `\"tool not found\"` responses per session. After **3 consecutive** unresolved tool_call attempts:\n\n1. Synthesize a final tool_result that says: \"You have attempted to call 3 tools that do not exist in this session: {list of attempted names}. Respond to the user without tool calls.\"\n2. Force the next provider call to use a synthesized `stop_reason: \"end_turn\"` constraint (if the provider supports it) OR detect end_turn in the model's next response and break the loop.\n3. Emit an `AgentEvent::ToolNotFoundLoopAborted` event so observability captures this happened.\n4. Telemetry (`task_telemetry`) gains a `tool_not_found_loop_aborted: bool` field so post-hoc analysis can count occurrences.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- Reproducer: with the no-tools-clause from sibling bead REVERTED (so the model still tries to call tools), a `mu ask` against a known-hallucinator model breaks out of the loop after 3 attempts instead of going to 6+.\n- `AgentEvent::ToolNotFoundLoopAborted` is emitted at the abort point with the list of attempted tool names.\n- `task_telemetry.tool_not_found_loop_aborted` is `true` for the aborted session.\n- Sessions with legitimate tool use (registered tools, valid calls) continue to work normally.\n- Configurable threshold (`MU_TOOL_NOT_FOUND_LIMIT` env var or daemon config; default 3) so operators can tune.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Heuristics that try to map hallucinated tool names to registered ones (e.g. fuzzy-match `execute_bash` → `bash`). Tempting but introduces a different class of bug; leave for a future bead if the data justifies.\n\n## Provenance\n\nFiled 2026-05-22 by tcovert. Sibling to bead [the no-tools-clause one]. Both surfaced from mu-q3v6's post-merge validation reproducer (daemon f7b1715a207c7d97, session-1).","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-05-22T07:10:28.059570810Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-22T07:10:28.059570810Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["agent-loop","cost-prevention","safety","termination-guard","tool-use","wire-projection-followup"]}
