run `just ci-aipr` in the kept workspace (cache warm); if green, push agent/mu-sqn-2026-06-06 + PR with MU_SKIP_PR_CHECK=1; else abandon rev rrwzkqwr, sprint-end --force, and close as already-resolved. Full briefing: MORNING_2026-06-06-overnight.md.","created_at":"2026-06-06T09:10:49Z"},{"id":173,"issue_id":"mu-sqn","author":"tcovert","text":"Overnight worker (cc-personal-3366ff95), 2026-06-06 — GOOD NEWS UPDATE: the floor-pin is ci-green AND both reviewers APPROVE it. The only blocker is a reviewer-HARNESS bug (mu-1mvq), not the change.\n\n- `MU_REVIEW_FULL_FILES=0 scripts/ai-review.sh` on this diff → exit 0, PANEL PASS, both qwen3-coder:30b + gpt-oss:20b → VERDICT: APPROVE (full substantive reviews; verbatim in MORNING_2026-06-06-overnight.md).\n- Default `just ci-aipr` (FULL_FILES=1) → exit 3, but that is the mu-1mvq full-file-context-overflow false-ESCALATE (reviewers truncated to 1 word), NOT a verdict on the change.\n\nPer protocol (worker does not override on exit 3) I opened NO PR and parked. DIRECTOR one-click promote (verified path): cd <mu-checkout> && MU_REVIEW_FULL_FILES=0 just ci-aipr (→0) → jj bookmark create agent/mu-sqn-2026-06-06 -r @ → jj git push → PR with MU_SKIP_PR_CHECK=1 from backing repo. OR MU_REVIEW_OVERRIDE=1 on the default gate now that the disproof is on record. OR abandon (advisories already clear on main; this is a regression guard). Rev rrwzkqwr, workspace KEPT, claim HELD.","created_at":"2026-06-06T09:18:58Z"}]}
 {"id":"mu-ssuh","title":"mu: AWS-capability integration — STS provenance + structured events + smoke tests + schema + AwsCapability requirement + narrower namespaces [umbrella]","description":"## Provenance\n\nArchitectural direction from gpt-5.5 conversation in mu daemon\nf3845422 session-4 (2026-05-16), prompted by review of\n`~/src/personal/mu-aws-sandbox-infra` (event 270; gpt's response at\nevent 350).\n\n## Vision\n\nAWS as the first hard-enforcement proving ground for the\ncapability-governed operating model:\n\n```text\nhuman intent\n  → mu session/delegation capability\n    → named AWS capability (e.g., aws.scout.readonly)\n      → local profile / STS role materialization\n        → IAM-enforced authority\n          → CloudTrail-auditable action\n```\n\nKey property: **AWS becomes the enforcement layer, not the prompt.**\nCapability names become operator vocabulary humans can reason about,\nagents can request, brokers can grant, logs can record, AWS can\nenforce. The bridge between human governance and machine enforcement.\n\n## Six concrete primitives to land\n\n### 1. STS session naming contract\n\nRunner assumes roles with session name embedding mu provenance:\n\n```text\nmu-<session_id>-<tool_call_id>-<short_nonce>\n```\n\nExport to runner env:\n- `MU_AWS_SESSION_NAME`\n- `MU_AWS_ROLE_ARN`\n- `MU_AWS_CAPABILITY`\n\nMakes mu-event-log → STS session name → CloudTrail join real and\nqueryable end-to-end.\n\n### 2. Runner emits structured event JSON\n\nOptional JSON event output that mu ingests as a tool-result sidecar\nor first-class event payload:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"kind\": \"aws_capability_materialized\",\n  \"capability\": \"aws.scout.readonly\",\n  \"profile\": \"mu-readonly-scout\",\n  \"role_arn\": \"...\",\n  \"region\": \"us-east-1\",\n  \"mutation_allowed\": false,\n  \"mu_session_id\": \"...\",\n  \"mu_tool_call_id\": \"...\",\n  \"aws_sts_session_name\": \"...\"\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Denied-action smoke tests per capability\n\nFirst-class smoke test infrastructure:\n\n```sh\nscripts/capability-smoke-test.sh aws.scout.readonly\nscripts/capability-smoke-test.sh aws.sandbox.build\n```\n\nEach capability proves: one allowed thing works; one forbidden thing\nfails (denied by IAM); mutation capabilities clean up after themselves.\n\n### 4. Capability schema validation\n\nJSON schema / Python validator for `capabilities/aws.json`:\n- known fields only\n- `planned` caps cannot have profile/role until status active\n- `active` caps must have profile/role_arn\n- `mutation_allowed: true` requires constraints or explicit\n  justification\n- `smoke_tests` present for active caps\n\n### 5. Mu-side aws_tool requires active AwsCapability — fail closed\n\nWhen integrated into mu, AWS tool MUST require an active\nAwsCapability. No fallback to host AWS env. No \"if capability missing,\njust use default profile.\" Dangerous failure mode: agent accidentally\ninherits operator's personal/admin AWS environment.\n\n### 6. Narrower readonly namespaces\n\n`aws.scout.readonly` works for sandbox but is too broad for\nproduction. AWS ReadOnlyAccess can still expose: SSM parameter\ncontents, Secrets Manager metadata, IAM topology, bucket names, tags,\nnetwork layout, account structure, logs, snapshots/backups metadata.\n\nSplit into:\n```text\naws.network.readonly\naws.iam.audit\naws.ec2.inventory\naws.s3.inventory\naws.cloudtrail.audit\naws.cost.readonly\n```\n\nThe planned `aws.network.readonly` capability already points this way.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nFull accountability chain becomes real:\n\n```text\nmu session id / tool call id\n  → MU_AWS_CAPABILITY\n    → STS session name/id\n      → CloudTrail events\n```\n\nModel intent → runtime materialization → infrastructure fact. Much\nmore serious than just an agent transcript.\n\n## Cross-refs\n\n- `~/src/personal/mu-aws-sandbox-infra` (the AWS capability lab)\n- OS-enforced sandboxing umbrella (sister bead — OS-layer enforcement)\n- Accountable-work-runtime umbrella (sister bead — actor-layer)\n- mu-hh1 (SupervisorCapability axis)\n- mu-dq5 / aws_recon (prior AWS capability work, merged)\n- Memory: enforcement-layer-stack philosophy (filed same session)\n- Provenance: gpt-5.5 architectural conversation, daemon f3845422\n  session-4 event 350 (2026-05-16)","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-05-16T07:15:25.849487157Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-16T07:15:25.849487157Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","aws","capability","integration","mu-coding","mu-core","observability","umbrella"]}
